did.abstract: These records are office files maintained by Siena's office during his term as Legal Advisor to the President. Primary concerns were faculty and student affairs, campus security and demonstrations, personnel, university and government relations. The files include correspondence, memoranda, notes and supporting documents.

separatedmaterial.head: Separated Materials
separatedmaterial.p: The following materials were removed from the collection.
Federal regulations and xeroxes of pages from the federal register unless specifically part of a letter or other communication.
Published pamphlets regarding the by-laws, charters, etc., of boards of trustees or overseers of major U.S. colleges and universities.
Duplicates of Stanford related published documents.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: The material is arranged in eleven series: 1. Campus disruptions, 2. Campus security, 3. Faculty affairs, 4. Government relations, 5. Personnel, 6. Lands and buildings, 7. Schools and departments, 8. Student affairs, 9. University relations, 10. Miscellaneous, 11. Additional material.

Box Series 1 Campus Disruptions 2 Campus Security 3 Faculty Affairs 4 Government Relations 5 Personnel 6 Lands and Buildings (A to F) 7 (d.b.) Lands and Buildings (G to Z) Schools and Departments 8 Student Affairs 9 Student Affairs University Relations 10 Miscellaneous 11-21 Additional material
All boxes are record storage cartons except #7, a document box.

accessrestrict.head: Information about Access
accessrestrict.p: Restricted: written permission required from President's Office until documents are 25 years old. For more information, contact the University Archivist.

userestrict.head: Ownership & Copyright
userestrict.p: All requests to reproduce, publish, quote from, or otherwise use collection materials must be submitted in writing to the Head of Special Collections and University Archives, Stanford University Libraries, Stanford, California 94304-6064. Consent is given on behalf of Special Collections as the owner of the physical items and is not intended to include or imply permission from the copyright owner. Such permission must be obtained from the copyright owner, heir(s) or assigns. See: http://library.stanford.edu/depts/spc/pubserv/permissions.html.
Restrictions also apply to digital representations of the original materials. Use of digital files is restricted to research and educational purposes.

bioghist.head: Biographical/Historical Sketch
bioghist.p: A Stanford law graduate (1961), Siena was appointed legal advisor to the President of the University in January 1970. Formerly associated with Covington & Burling, a prominent Washington D. C. law firm, Siena later served in the Department of the Army as Deputy Under Secretary for International Affairs. He also served as a consultant to the Office of Economic Opportunity and a member of the Board of the National Capital Area Civil Liberties Union.

As Legal Advisor to the President, Siena worked with Presidents Kenneth Pitzer (January 1970 to September 1970) and Richard Lyman (September 1970 to 1977) as well as the provost and other university officials on legal matters. He acted as liaison with outside counsel, reviewed campus operations in light of existing laws and regulations, and monitored legislative and regulatory changes affecting the University.

scopecontent.head: Description of the Collection
scopecontent.p: These records are office files maintained by Siena's office during his term as Legal Advisor to the President. Primary concerns were faculty and student affairs, campus security and demonstrations, personnel, university and government relations. The files include correspondence, memoranda, notes and supporting documents.

processinfo.head: Processing Information
processinfo.p: The files were received from the President's Office in no evident alphabetical, chronological or series order. Series were reestablished in processing based on abbreviations on folder labels designating "personnel" "faculty affairs," etc. Several folders had no distinguishing notation and were not obviously part of any of the established series; these folders were placed at the end of the collection as a miscellaneous unit.
